library(dplyr) # data manipulation

1. Introduction

The question of this study is to understand how Birth rate of a country is relative to factors such as:

  • Geography: Area,
  • People and Society: Population, Median age,
  • Economy: Labor force, Inflation rate,
  • Communications: number of users within a country that access the Internet,
  • Transportaion: number of Airports.

The linear regression model is the primary method for this task. And two additional modeling techque are include just for chanllenge myself:

  • Simple linear regression model
  • Generalized linear Model
  • Generalized Additive Model

2. Dataset

The data is obtained by using web scraping on the The World Factbook published by CIA.

library(rvest)
library(tidyverse)
library(furrr)
library(tictoc)
source("ud_function.R")
plan(multiprocess) # switch to parallel computing

# the base url
url <- "https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/resources/the-world-factbook/docs/rankorderguide.html"

# extract href and the relevent text from base url, and form dataframe df
href <- read_html(url) %>% html_nodes(".field_label") %>% html_nodes("strong a") %>% html_attr(name="href")
t <- read_html(url) %>% html_nodes(".field_label") %>% html_nodes("strong a") %>% html_text()
df <- data.frame(t = t, href = href, stringsAsFactors = FALSE) %>%
  mutate_all(as.character())

# map the scrapone() function to each row of dataset df
tic()
table <- furrr::future_map2_dfr(df$href, df$t, function(x,y) scrapOne(x = x, url= url, t= y))
toc()
## 4.608 sec elapsed
plan(sequential) # back to sequential computing
# use user-defined function to clear the dataset
table <- table %>% group_by(Country) %>% summarise_all(coalesce_by_column)
table <- table %>% group_by(Country) %>% mutate_if(is.character,cleanText) %>% mutate_all(as.numeric)
colnames(table) <- gsub(":", "", colnames(table))
colnames(table) <- gsub(" ", "", colnames(table))

n_na <- colSums(!is.na(table))
n <- n_na[n_na>225] %>% names
table_subset <- table[colnames(table) %in% n]

table_subset <- table_subset %>%
  ungroup() %>% 
  rename(Inflationrate = "Inflationrate(consumerprices)") %>% 
  select(-Country) %>% 
  select(-Populationgrowthrate, -Deathrate, -Netmigrationrate) %>% 
  select(Birthrate,everything())
colnames(table_subset) <- gsub("-", "", colnames(table_subset))

3. Simple Linear Regression Model

By doing a exhaustive search for all possible combinations including interactions, the best linear model for first order and quadratic order are the following:

  • lm(formula = Birthrate ~ Medianage) with adjusted \(R^2 = 0.849\)
  • lm(Birthrate ~ Area + Medianage + Inflationrate + Airports + Area:Medianage + Population:Airports + Medianage:Inflationrate + Medianage:Airports) with adjusted \(R^2 = 0.8773\)

All estimated slope are statistically significant with alpha of 0.05 as shown in the following outputs. By following the principle of Ockham’s razor, I decide to take the lm(formula = Birthrate ~ Medianage) as the best linear model.

library(leaps)
#model selection
# all except Birthrate to be the expanatory variable
lm_p1 <- regsubsets(Birthrate ~ ., data=table_subset, method='exhaustive', nbest=30, really.big=T) %>% summary()
lm_p2 <- regsubsets(Birthrate ~ .^2, data=table_subset, method='exhaustive', nbest=30, really.big=T) %>% summary()
lm_p3 <- regsubsets(Birthrate ~ .^3, data=table_subset, method='exhaustive', nbest=30, really.big=T) %>% summary()
lm <- list(lm_p1, lm_p2, lm_p3)

5. Alternative Model

5.1 Generalized linear Model

As a U shape shown in the residual plot from the one variable linear model, I suggest to use a generalized linear Model using a inverse linkage function of Gamma family.

glm_p1 <- glm(Birthrate ~ Medianage, family = Gamma(),
              data = table_subset)
summary(glm_p1)

5.2 Generalized Additive Model

Alternative, I suggest a Generalized Additive Model model could better fit this data.

library(mgcv)
gam_p1 <- gam(Birthrate ~ s(Medianage),
              data = table_subset, method = "REML", select = TRUE)
plot(gam_p1, shift = coef(gam_p1)[1],
     seWithMean = TRUE, residuals = TRUE,
     se = TRUE, shade = TRUE, 
     rug = TRUE, pch = 1)

  • The effective degree of freedom edf equal to 6, refering to a complex and wiggly weight smoothing.
  • The Ref.df and F columns are test statistics used in an ANOVA test to test overall significance of the smooth, and it show the the smoothing is siginificant with alpha of 0.05, indicating 95% confidence of the smoothed shape.
  • The \(R^2\) is 0.965, which higher than the linear regression model.

5. Conclusion

Within the scope of the requirement, I conclude the best linear regresssion model for this dataset is the model with only one variabl Medianage:

\(BirthRate_{pred} = 48.572 - 0.96087 \times Median Age, R^2 = 0.852\)

The p-value for intercept and slope are signficant. It shows that the the estimated value for the coefficient is not equal to zero 0.

However, the assumption of linearity is violated as shown in the residual plot. Some outlier also affect the fit of the model.

Based on the linear model, we expect a 0.96% decrease in Birth Rate with one year increase in Median Age for a country.

A. Reference: User-defined Function

# user-defined function to scrap table from one href 
scrapOne <- function(x, url, t){
  url_abs<-url_absolute(x,base=url)
  table <- read_html(url_abs) %>% html_table
  table <- table[[1]][,2:3] %>% as_tibble() %>% setNames(nm= c("Country",t))
  return(table)
}

# user-defined function to clean the text
cleanText <- function(x){
  x <- gsub("[[:blank:]]", "", x) 
  x <- as.numeric(gsub(",","",x))
  x <-  gsub("\n", "", x) # clean up the links names
  return(x)
}

# user-defined function to coalesce the table
coalesce_by_column <- function(df) {
  return(dplyr::coalesce(!!! as.list(df)))
}
